## World 2: Regular Tenant Users (HR, Payroll, Finance, Employee)

Once they've accepted their invite and set their password, every subsequent login is identical regardless of role.

**Login screen** — `app.payrollapp.com/login`

Just like the **GTBank mobile app** login or **Carbon loan app** — email field, password field, Login button. Maybe a "Forgot password?" link. No company name field. No tenant code. The system looks up their email in the database, finds which company they belong to, and routes them in.

What if someone from Zenith and someone from Dangote have the same email? That shouldn't happen — email is unique across the entire platform. One person, one account. If someone genuinely works for two companies (a consultant for instance), they'd need two separate email addresses for each company account.

**After login — what each person sees:**

This is where it diverges completely based on role.

---

### HR Manager (Amaka's flow)

She logs in and lands on a **dashboard** that looks like the main screen of **Workday** or a simplified **BambooHR** — her primary concern is people.

Her dashboard shows:
- Total headcount
- New joiners this month
- Upcoming contract end dates
- Employees with incomplete records (missing bank details etc.)

Her navigation menu has:
- **Employees** — the main area she lives in
- **Organisation** — legal entities, departments, locations
- **Reports** — HR-specific reports

She clicks **Employees**. She sees a data table — think of the **Flutterwave transactions list** but for people. Search bar at top, filter by department/location/status, paginated list of employees. Each row: name, employee ID, job title, department, status (active/on leave/exited).

She clicks **Add Employee**. A multi-step form opens — like filling a **NIN enrollment form** or a **NYSC portal form**. Step 1 is personal details (name, DOB, gender, contact). Step 2 is employment details (start date, department, job title, employment type). Step 3 is compensation (salary amount, currency, effective from date — this is that effective-dating field). Step 4 is bank details (for salary payment). Step 5 is review and submit.

She submits. The employee record is created. If the employee portal is enabled, an invite email goes to that employee automatically.

When she needs to give Chidi a raise in October, she goes to his profile, clicks **Compensation**, sees a timeline of his salary history (this looks like a **Cowrywise savings history** — entries with dates), and clicks **Add New Entry**. She enters ₦350,000 and "effective from October 1st." The old ₦280,000 record stays untouched. The system now knows: before October, use ₦280,000. October onwards, use ₦350,000. When October payroll runs, it automatically picks the right figure.

---

### Payroll Manager (Emeka's flow)

He logs in and lands on a **payroll-focused dashboard**. His primary concern is runs and deadlines.

His dashboard shows:
- Upcoming pay dates (like a calendar widget)
- Status of current pay runs (Draft / In Review / Approved / Paid)
- Any flagged issues from the last calculation

His navigation has:
- **Pay Runs** — main area
- **Pay Elements** — tax rules, allowances, deductions setup
- **Reports** — payroll register, statutory reports

He clicks **Pay Runs → New Run**. A setup screen appears — think of initiating a **transfer on the GTBank app** but for payroll. He selects:
- Pay group: Lagos Monthly Staff
- Pay period: July 2026

He clicks **Create**. The run is created in **Draft** state. He sees a run detail screen showing the 87 employees who will be included, their basic salary figures pulled from their records. He hasn't calculated yet — this is just the preview.

He clicks **Calculate**. This triggers the backend engine. A **progress indicator** appears — like the spinning/loading state on a **Flutterwave bulk transfer** or how **Kuda** shows "processing" for transfers. The calculation runs in the background. The page either polls for updates or receives a live signal when it's done.

When calculation finishes, the run moves to **Calculated** state. The page refreshes to show the full register — a detailed table of every employee, every element (basic salary, transport allowance, PAYE tax, pension, net pay). He can click into any employee row to see their individual breakdown.

He spots Bola's ₦0 issue. He flags it via a comment or goes to HR to fix the record. Once fixed, he clicks **Recalculate** — which reruns just Bola's calculation (or the whole run depending on implementation).

Satisfied, he clicks **Submit for Approval**. The run moves to **In Review** state. His approve button disappears — he can no longer touch it. A notification goes to Mrs. Okonkwo.

---

### Finance Director (Mrs. Okonkwo's flow)

She logs in and lands on a **finance-focused dashboard** — her concern is money leaving the company and compliance.

She sees:
- Payroll runs awaiting her approval (highlighted, with urgency indicator if pay date is close)
- Total payroll cost this month vs last month vs budget
- Upcoming statutory filing deadlines (PAYE remittance to FIRS is due by the 10th of every month)

She clicks the notification/alert for July Lagos payroll. She lands on the run detail screen in **read-only mode** — she can see everything Emeka saw but cannot edit anything. Her available action is just the **Approve** button (and a **Reject/Send Back** button with a comment box if something is wrong).

She reviews. She clicks **Approve**. A **confirmation modal** appears — think of how **Kuda or Opay** asks "Are you sure you want to send ₦24.3M?" with a summary. She confirms.

The run moves to **Approved** state. Several things happen automatically in the background:
- All 87 payslips are generated as PDFs and stored
- Employees who have portal access get email notifications "Your July payslip is ready"
- The payroll register is available for download as Excel
- Statutory remittance reports are available for download

She then goes to the **Payments** section. She sees the approved run. She clicks **Download Payment File**. The system generates the bulk payment file in the format configured for the company's bank (e.g., GTBank bulk transfer Excel template). She downloads it, logs into GTBank Business Internet Banking separately (outside this app), uploads the file there, and authorizes the transfers. That's the money moving.

---

### Employee (Chidi's flow)

Chidi got an invite email when Amaka added him. He set his password. He logs in.

His dashboard is the most minimal of all — like the **PiggyVest** or **Carbon** home screen but with almost nothing to do except view. He sees:

- His name and employee ID
- His current salary (if the company has enabled this visibility)
- His latest payslip with a quick summary
- A notification if a new payslip is available

His navigation is tiny:
- **My Payslips** — list of all his payslips, click any to view the PDF or see it rendered on screen. He can download any one as PDF for bank loan applications.
- **My Profile** — his personal details. He can update his home address, phone number, next of kin. He *cannot* update his salary or job title — that's HR's job.
- **My Bank Details** — he can view and update his bank account number. Some companies lock this so only HR can change it (to prevent fraud).

That's his entire world. Clean, simple, nothing he doesn't need.

